{"title_page": "Imageboard", "text_new": "Uskid t\u00fa un John buen hecho BGH hola hola\n\nAn '''imageboard''' is a type of [[Internet forum]] that revolves around the posting of images, often alongside related text and discussion. The first imageboards were created in [[Japan]] as an extension of the [[textboard]] concept. These sites later inspired the creation of a number of [[English language|English-language]] imageboards, such as [[4chan]].\n\n== Characteristics ==\nImageboards, similar to [[bulletin board system]]s, are used for discussions of a variety of topics. The primary focus of imageboards, however, is directed away from text posts, and is instead placed on picture posts. The two share many of the same structures, including separate forums for separate topics, as well as similar audiences. Imageboards are much more transitory with content\u2014on some boards (especially highly trafficked ones), the thread deletion time can be as little as 10 minutes. In [[Japan]], where imageboards are more common{{citation needed|reason=Needs proof not just assumption|date=April 2016}}, topics will vary widely, ranging from [[train]]s to current [[news]]. The most popular [[English language]] imageboard, [[4chan]], similarly has a large  variety of topics.\n\nImageboards are also different from [[image hosting service|online galleries]] in that most of the works posted are not made by the poster, but instead are taken from other online sources: galleries, other imageboards, and edited pictures.\n\n=== Tripcodes ===\n[[File:Tripcode generation diagram.svg|thumb|right|300px|A diagram of a typical tripcode derivation process.]]\nMost imageboards and [[2channel]]-style discussion boards allow (and encourage) [[anonymous post]]ing and use a system of ''tripcodes'' instead of registration. A tripcode is the [[Hash function|hashed]] result of a password that allows one's identity to be recognized without storing any data about users. Entering a particular password will let one \"sign\" one's posts with the tripcode generated from that password, while trying to take another user's tripcode and compute their password from it (for instance, to make posts that appear to come from a particular person) is computationally difficult. For those who want a custom tripcode, however, there are custom tripcode generators (which are technically tripcode crackers) available, such as Meriken's Tripcode Engine<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/meriken/merikens-tripcode-engine-v3|title=\"Meriken's Tripcode Engine\" is a cross-platform custom tripcode generator.: meriken/merikens-tripcode-engine-v3|date=26 March 2019|publisher=|via=GitHub}}</ref> and MTY_CL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/madsbuvi/MTY_CL|title=A custom tripcode searcher, written using OpenCL. Primarily targeting the GCN architectures (Radeon HD 77xx and later).: madsbuvi/MTY_CL|date=9 March 2019|publisher=|via=GitHub}}</ref> In general, anonymity is considered to be one of the advantages of an imageboard, and some boards have from time to time removed the ability to post with a name altogether (known as \"forced anonymous/anonymity\").\n\n== Software ==\nThere are two primary types of imageboard software packages in widespread use:{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} linearly directed imageboards modeled closely after Futaba Channel (in which content is posted through hierarchical subsections of topical interest, usually denoted by a forward slash such as \"/f\" for female), and nonlinear imageboards modeled after [[#Danbooru-style boards|Danbooru]] (usually indicated by the usage of [[controlled vocabulary|controlled]] [[folksonomy|folksonomic]] vocabulary for topical tagging and search).\n\n=== Futaba Channel clones ===\nThere are currently several Futaba-based imageboard software packages in widespread use: ''Futallaby'', ''Wakaba'', ''Kusaba X''.\n\n''Futallaby'' is a [[PHP]] script based on the Futaba script from [[Futaba Channel]]. Although  the Futallaby source is still freely available at 1chan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1chan.net/futallaby/ |title=Futallaby Imageboard Script |publisher=1chan.net |date= |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> it is no longer in development, and the download page recommends using Wakaba instead, stating that \"Wakaba can do everything Futallaby does and so much more.\" Futallaby started as a translation of Futaba, later retooled to support XHTML and customizable CSS styles. It is mostly notable for being the first [[open source]] English imageboard script.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n''Wakaba'' is a [[Perl]] imageboard script with a SQL backend to store thread information.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wakaba.c3.cx |title=wakaba.c3.cx |publisher=wakaba.c3.cx |date= |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> It is designed to be more efficient and cleanly written than other scripts that are available, while preserving the same kind of functionality. Wakaba is one of the most popular western imageboard software scripts,{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} used most notably by iichan (''Wakachan'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wakachan.org/ |title=wakachan.org |publisher=wakachan.org |date= |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> Because of its focus on bare-bones functionality, Wakaba lacks many of the modern amenities provided by 4chan's Yotsuba,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4chan.org/news?all#108 |title=4chan Inline Extension News Post}}</ref> and newer imageboard scripts. A few users have attempted to remedy this by [[Fork (software development)|forking]] the original project and adding in features they consider beneficial. Two [[FOSS]] examples of this are frankusr's Wakaba fork,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/frankusrs/Wakaba |title=frankusr's Wakaba Fork Repository}}</ref> and the user experience focused ''Glaukaba''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/marlencrabapple/Glaukaba |title=Glaukaba Imageboard Script}}</ref>\n\n''Kusaba'' was a modular imageboard software written in PHP, which used [[MySQL]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/tslocum/kusaba |title=Kusaba Imageboard Script |author=tslocum |publisher=GitHub |date= |accessdate=2013-06-06}}</ref> The creator has discontinued the project, however, and recommends TinyIB instead.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n''Kusaba X'' is a continuation of Kusaba. Like Kusaba, Kusaba X is written in PHP, and is designed with modularity in mind. It requires a [[MySQL]] or [[SQLite]] database to run. Kusaba and its derivatives were at one time some of the most popular imageboard solutions.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} Kusaba X has since fallen out of active development, and has not been updated since July 2011.\n\n''Tinyboard'' is a PHP based imageboard script with a MySQL backend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/savetheinternet/Tinyboard |title=Tinyboard - The better imageboard software |author=savetheinternet |publisher=GitHub |date= |accessdate=2017-07-13}}</ref> It was eventually discontinued and forked into ''vichan'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/vichan-devel/vichan |title=vichan - Tinyboard branch taking lightweightness somewhat more liberally |author=czaks |publisher=GitHub |date= |accessdate=2017-07-13}}</ref> which itself was forked into ''infinity''<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/ctrlcctrlv/infinity |title=infinity - A vichan fork permitting users to create their own boards |author=ctrlcctrlv |publisher=GitHub |date= |accessdate=2017-07-13}}</ref> and later ''infinity'' was forked into ''OpenIB.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/OpenIB/OpenIB |title=OpenIB - An infinity fork focused on security. |author=Cipherwraith |publisher=GitHub |date= |accessdate=2017-07-13}}</ref> Tinyboard (and its forks) notably feature extensibility with JavaScript<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/vichan-devel/vichan/issues/252 |title=Cool codes js to improve vichan? #252 |accessdate=2017-07-13}}</ref> and the infinity and OpenIB forks include user-submitted board creation.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n''Lynxchan'' is an imageboard based on [[JavaScript]] and [[Node.js]]. It requires a [[MongoDB]] database to run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gitgud.io/LynxChan/LynxChan |title=LynxChan - The best chan engine that you will ever shitpost with.  |author=Stephen Lynx |publisher=GitGud |date= |accessdate=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n''sukiyaki'' A futaba-style imageboard script that doesn't require a database.\n[[PHP]]<ref>https://github.com/iyra/sukiyaki sukiyaki </ref>\n\n''shittyboard'' is a small imageboard script that doesn't require a database (uses CSV-like file in order to store posts) and provides unique captcha, that can filter out not only bots, but also people, who don't know anything about the topic and don't want to educate themselves. It is best suited for low-traffic use-cases, and it comes pre-configured, which makes installing this script super easy. Works perfectly with older web-browsers.\n[[PHP]]<ref>https://github.com/shittyboard/shittyboard</ref>\n\n=== Danbooru-style boards ===\n\nUsually referred to as a \"[[wikt:booru|booru]]\" (plural \"boorus\"). Unlike Futaba-inspired imageboard software packages, Danbooru and derivatives aim for a non-hierarchical semantic structure in which users are able to post content and add [[tag (metadata)|tag]]s, annotations, translations, artist commentary, and comments.\n\nThere exist a number of different Danbooru-style imageboards, both those with shared source code and those that are not released for others to use. The two main Danbooru derivatives are Gelbooru and MyImouto.\n<!--\nSome imageboard engines have a public API which can be used to automate publication and post viewing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gelbooru.com/index.php?page=help&topic=dapi |title=Gelbooru |publisher=Gelbooru |date= |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://danbooru.donmai.us/help/api |title=Danbooru |publisher=Danbooru.donmai.us |date= |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref> A de facto standard for the API, created by Danbooru and used by the other imageboards has been established for this. The feature is used by a number of board crawlers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibsearch.i-forge.net/ |title=Imageboards Searcher |publisher=I-forge.net |date= |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tenshichan.com/ |title=Safe Imageboards Search Engine |publisher=Tenshichan.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-04}}</ref> and Firefox extensions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/danbooru/ |title=danbooru :: Add-ons for Firefox |last=Hayashime |first=Atachi |publisher=Addons.mozilla.org |date=2007-03-25 |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://danbooru.donmai.us/help/extension |title=Danbooru |publisher=Danbooru.donmai.us |date= |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref>\n-->\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Traits of Danbooru-style imageboards\n! Shared !! Software !! Programmed in !! License !! Notes\n|-\n| {{Yes}} || [https://github.com/r888888888/danbooru Danbooru] || [[Ruby on Rails]] || {{free|[[FreeBSD License#2-clause license .28.22Simplified BSD License.22 or .22FreeBSD License.22.29|FreeBSD]]}} || Uses [[PostgreSQL]].<ref>From [https://github.com/r888888888/danbooru/blob/master/README Readme]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} of the source code.</ref>\n|-\n| {{Yes}} || [http://code.shishnet.org/shimmie2/ Shimmie 2] || [[PHP]] || {{free|[[GPL#Version 2|GPLv2]]}} || Uses [[MySQL]] by default (as part of LAMP), can also use PostgreSQL.\n|-\n| {{Yes}} || [https://github.com/digiwombat/naranai naranai 1.3.x] || [[PHP]] || {{free|[[GPL#Version 3|GPLv3]]}} || Uses MySQL. Built to replace Danbooru because author considered Ruby unsuitable.<ref>From [https://github.com/digiwombat/naranai/blob/master/README Readme] of the source code.</ref>\n|-\n| {{Yes}} || [https://github.com/rr-/szurubooru szurubooru] || [[Python (programming language)|Python]] || {{free|[[GPL#Version 3|GPLv3]]}} || Uses PostgreSQL.\n|-